{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775852778397,"sessionID":"ses_286ed4f0bffefmfnGF4OM7xCV9","part":{"id":"prt_d7912f11e001B3tlk5wJFhTLtz","messageID":"msg_d7912de640010l74VnEb0XO2PM","sessionID":"ses_286ed4f0bffefmfnGF4OM7xCV9","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-1fff7a3edaa14a59a80d4a0228b772c3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-009 Delta-Spec\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: Implement the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality for the Router component, providing request routing to sandbox endpoints with JWT authentication, health endpoints, and concurrency management.\n5: \n6: ## Base Specs\n7: - deployment/client-go.md: Kubernetes client library for runtime API types (AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter)\n8: \n9: ## Requirements\n10: \n11: ### Requirement: HTTP server initialization\n12: The system SHALL provide a configurable HTTP server that listens on a specified port, supports both HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2 (h2c), with configurable timeouts and optional TLS support.\n13: \n14: #### Scenario: Server starts on configured port\n15: - **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called with `Port: 8080`\n16: - **WHEN** `Start` is invoked\n17: - **THEN** the server listens on port 8080 and accepts HTTP connections\n18: \n19: #### Scenario: Server starts with TLS enabled\n20: - **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called with `EnableTLS: true`, `TLSCertPath: \"/certs/cert.pem\"`, and `TLSKeyPath: \"/certs/key.pem\"`\n21: - **WHEN** `Start` is invoked\n22: - **THEN** the server uses TLS with the provided certificate and key files\n23: \n24: #### Scenario: Server fails with invalid TLS configuration\n25: - **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called with `EnableTLS: true` and empty cert or key path\n26: - **WHEN** `Start` is invoked\n27: - **THEN** it returns an error indicating certificate and key are required\n28: \n29: #### Scenario: Server applies configured timeouts\n30: - **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called with `ReadTimeout: 30s` and `IdleTimeout: 90s`\n31: - **WHEN** the server is running\n32: - **THEN** HTTP reads timeout after 30s and idle connections close after 90s\n33: \n34: #### Scenario: Server shuts down gracefully\n35: - **GIVEN** the server is running and context is cancelled\n36: - **WHEN** shutdown is triggered\n37: - **THEN** the server stops accepting new connections and waits up to 10s for active connections to complete\n38: \n39: ### Requirement: Reverse proxy configuration\n40: The system SHALL provide reverse proxy functionality to forward HTTP requests to upstream sandbox endpoints, handling URL construction, protocol detection, and proper request/response forwarding.\n41: \n42: #### Scenario: Proxy forwards to upstream endpoint\n43: - **GIVEN** a reverse proxy is configured with upstream URL `http://sandbox-pod:8080`\n44: - **WHEN** an incoming request is received\n45: - **THEN** the proxy forwards the request to the upstream URL and returns the response\n46: \n47: #### Scenario: Proxy constructs URL with protocol prefix\n48: - **GIVEN** sandbox info with `Protocol: \"http\"` and `Endpoint: \"sandbox-pod:8080\"`\n49: - **WHEN** the upstream URL is constructed\n50: - **THEN** the URL becomes `http://sandbox-pod:8080`\n51: \n52: #### Scenario: Proxy uses endpoint as-is when scheme present\n53: - **GIVEN** sandbox info with `Protocol: \"\"` and `Endpoint: \"https://sandbox-pod:8080\"`\n54: - **WHEN** the upstream URL is constructed\n55: - **THEN** the URL remains `https://sandbox-pod:8080`\n56: \n57: #### Scenario: Proxy handles multiple entry points\n58: - **GIVEN** sandbox info with entry points `[{\"path\": \"/api\", \"endpoint\": \"api:8080\"}, {\"path\": \"/\", \"endpoint\": \"web:8080\"}]`\n59: - **WHEN** a request to `/api/v1/data` is received\n60: - **THEN** the proxy routes to `api:8080`\n61: \n62: #### Scenario: Proxy uses first entry point for non-matching paths\n63: - **GIVEN** sandbox info with entry points `[{\"path\": \"/api\", \"endpoint\": \"api:8080\"}, {\"path\": \"/\", \"endpoint\": \"web:8080\"}]`\n64: - **WHEN** a request to `/health` is received\n65: - **THEN** the proxy routes to `web:8080` (first entry point with path \"/\")\n66: \n67: ### Requirement: Request forwarding headers\n68: The system SHALL set standard forwarding headers on proxied requests, including X-Forwarded-Host, X-Forwarded-Proto, and X-Forwarded-For.\n69: \n70: #### Scenario: Proxy sets X-Forwarded-Host\n71: - **GIVEN** an incoming request with Host header `example.com`\n72: - **WHEN** the proxy forwards the request\n73: - **THEN** the proxied request includes `X-Forwarded-Host: example.com`\n74: \n75: #### Scenario: Proxy sets X-Forwarded-Proto based on TLS\n76: - **GIVEN** TLS is enabled and an incoming request is received\n77: - **WHEN** the proxy forwards the request\n78: - **THEN** the proxied request includes `X-Forwarded-Proto: https`\n79: \n80: #### Scenario: Proxy sets X-Forwarded-Proto to http without TLS\n81: - **GIVEN** TLS is disabled and an incoming request is received\n82: - **WHEN** the proxy forwards the request\n83: - **THEN** the proxied request includes `X-Forwarded-Proto: http`\n84: \n85: #### Scenario: Proxy appends client IP to X-Forwarded-For\n86: - **GIVEN** an incoming request from client IP `10.0.0.5` and existing `X-Forwarded-For: 10.0.0.1`\n87: - **WHEN** the proxy forwards the request\n88: - **THEN** the proxied request includes `X-Forwarded-For: 10.0.0.1, 10.0.0.5`\n89: \n90: ### Requirement: JWT signing and injection\n91: The system SHALL generate and sign JWT tokens for authenticated requests to sandbox endpoints, injecting the token into the Authorization header.\n92: \n93: #### Scenario: Proxy generates JWT for sandbox request\n94: - **GIVEN** a JWT manager is configured with a signing key and the request target requires JWT\n95: - **WHEN** the proxy forwards a request\n96: - **THEN** the proxied request includes `Authorization: Bearer <signed-jwt>`\n97: \n98: #### Scenario: JWT signing failure blocks proxy\n99: - **GIVEN** JWT generation returns an error during request forwarding\n100: - **WHEN** the proxy attempts to forward the request\n101: - **THEN** the handler returns 500 with JSON `{\"code\":\"JWT_SIGNING_FAILED\",\"error\":\"failed to sign request\"}`\n102: \n103: #### Scenario: JWT manager loads keys from secret\n104: - **GIVEN** the JWT manager is initialized with secret `picod-router-identity` containing `private.pem` and `public.pem`\n105: - **WHEN** the server starts\n106: - **THEN** the JWT manager successfully loads the signing key from `private.pem`\n107: \n108: ### Requirement: Proxy error handling\n109: The system SHALL map reverse proxy errors to appropriate HTTP status codes and error messages for upstream failures.\n110: \n111: #### Scenario: Connection refused maps to 502\n112: - **GIVEN** the upstream endpoint refuses the connection\n113: - **WHEN** the proxy error handler is invoked\n114: - **THEN** the response is 502 with JSON `{\"error\":\"sandbox unreachable\"}`\n115: \n116: #### Scenario: Timeout maps to 504\n117: - **GIVEN** the upstream endpoint times out\n118: - **WHEN** the proxy error handler is invoked\n119: - **THEN** the response is 504 with JSON `{\"error\":\"sandbox timeout\"}`\n120: \n121: #### Scenario: Other errors map to 502\n122: - **GIVEN** the upstream endpoint returns any other error\n123: - **WHEN** the proxy error handler is invoked\n124: - **THEN** the response is 502 with JSON `{\"error\":\"sandbox unreachable\"}`\n125: \n126: ### Requirement: Health endpoints\n127: The system SHALL provide liveness and readiness endpoints for health checking.\n128: \n129: #### Scenario: Liveness endpoint returns success\n130: - **GIVEN** the server is running\n131: - **WHEN** `GET /health/live` is called\n132: - **THEN** the response is 200 with JSON `{\"status\":\"alive\"}`\n133: \n134: #### Scenario: Readiness endpoint returns success when dependencies ready\n135: - **GIVEN** all required dependencies (session manager, JWT manager) are initialized\n136: - **WHEN** `GET /health/ready` is called\n137: - **THEN** the response is 200 with JSON `{\"status\":\"ready\"}`\n138: \n139: #### Scenario: Readiness endpoint returns 503 when dependencies missing\n140: - **GIVEN** the session manager is not initialized\n141: - **WHEN** `GET /health/ready` is called\n142: - **THEN** the response is 503 with JSON including `\"error\":\"session manager not available\"`\n143: \n144: ### Requirement: Concurrency limiting\n145: The system SHALL apply a semaphore middleware to limit concurrent requests, preventing server overload.\n146: \n147: #### Scenario: Requests within limit are processed\n148: - **GIVEN** concurrency limit is 1000 and 500 concurrent requests are active\n149: - **WHEN** a new request arrives\n150: - **THEN** the request is processed normally\n151: \n152: #### Scenario: Requests over limit are rejected\n153: - **GIVEN** concurrency limit is 1000 and 1000 concurrent requests are active\n154: - **WHEN** a new request arrives\n155: - **THEN** the response is 429 with JSON `{\"error\":\"server overloaded, please try again later\",\"code\":\"SERVER_OVERLOADED\"}`\n156: \n157: #### Scenario: Default limit when config is zero\n158: - **GIVEN** `MaxConcurrentRequests` is set to 0\n159: - **WHEN** the server is initialized\n160: - **THEN** the effective limit is set to 1000\n161: \n162: ### Requirement: Route registration\n163: The system SHALL register HTTP routes for invocation endpoints, applying appropriate middleware chains.\n164: \n165: #### Scenario: Agent runtime invocation route is registered\n166: - **GIVEN** the server is initialized\n167: - **WHEN** routes are registered\n168: - **THEN** GET and POST are registered for `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path`\n169: \n170: #### Scenario: Code interpreter invocation route is registered\n171: - **GIVEN** the server is initialized\n172: - **WHEN** routes are registered\n173: - **THEN** GET and POST are registered for `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/code-interpreters/:name/invocations/*path`\n174: \n175: #### Scenario: Middleware chain is applied to v1 routes\n176: - **GIVEN** the server is initialized with logger, recovery, and concurrency middleware\n177: - **WHEN** routes under `/v1` are registered\n178: - **THEN** all v1 routes use the configured middleware chain\n179: \n180: ### Requirement: Response headers\n181: The system SHALL add response headers to indicate the session ID used for processing the request.\n182: \n183: #### Scenario: Session ID header is added to response\n184: - **GIVEN** a request is processed with session ID `abc123`\n185: - **WHEN** the response is sent\n186: - **THEN** the response includes header `x-agentcube-session-id: abc123`\n187: \n188: ### Requirement: Path normalization\n189: The system SHALL normalize request paths when forwarding, ensuring proper slash handling.\n190: \n191: #### Scenario: Path prefix is added when missing\n192: - **GIVEN** a Gin path parameter `api/v1/data` (without leading slash)\n193: - **WHEN** the director constructs the outbound path\n194: - **THEN** the path becomes `/api/v1/data`\n195: \n196: ### Requirement: Shared HTTP transport\n197: The system SHALL use a shared HTTP transport across all reverse proxy instances for optimal resource usage.\n198: \n199: #### Scenario: Multiple proxies share transport\n200: - **GIVEN** the server creates multiple reverse proxy instances\n201: - **WHEN** proxies are initialized\n202: - **THEN** all proxies share the same `http.Transport` instance\n203: \n204: ### Requirement: Configuration validation\n205: The system SHALL validate required configuration at server initialization.\n206: \n207: #### Scenario: Missing required port fails initialization\n208: - **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called without specifying port\n209: - **WHEN** initialization is attempted\n210: - **THEN** it returns an error indicating port is required\n211: \n212: #### Scenario: Invalid port number fails initialization\n213: - **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called with `Port: -1`\n214: - **WHEN** initialization is attempted\n215: - **THEN** it returns an error indicating invalid port number\n\n(End of file - total 215 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-009 Delta-Spec\n\n## Purpose\nImplement the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality for the Router component, providing request routing to sandbox endpoints with JWT authentication, health endpoints, and concurrency management.\n\n## Base Specs\n- deployment/client-go.md: Kubernetes client library for runtime API types (AgentRuntime, CodeInterpreter)\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: HTTP server initialization\nThe system SHALL provide a configurable HTTP server that listens on a specified port, supports both HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2 (h2c), with configurable timeouts and optional TLS support.\n\n#### Scenario: Server starts on configured port\n- **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called with `Port: 8080`\n- **WHEN** `Start` is invoked\n- **THEN** the server listens on port 8080 and accepts HTTP connections\n\n#### Scenario: Server starts with TLS enabled\n- **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called with `EnableTLS: true`, `TLSCertPath: \"/certs/cert.pem\"`, and `TLSKeyPath: \"/certs/key.pem\"`","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775852778367,"end":1775852778395}}}}
